column4: The e-commerce framework is fully integrated into pimcore. One system for pim, cms, dam and e-commerce.
Since it is fully integrated into pimcore, you can use the full power of pimcore within your shop application.
The framework approach gives you full flexibility in creating the optimal solution for your use case. No restrictions due to technology.

column4:
Within this pages, some special features of this demo are explained and linked. 

\
Special Functions implemented in this Demo

This demo uses a multi-level product model with following levels:

\

column2:
• Article: as product objects in pimcore (with blue icon).
    • \

• Color Variants: as product objects and direct children of Article objects (with green icon).
    • \

• Size Variants - concrete products: as pimcore variants of Color Variant objects.
    • \

column4:
For each product grid it is possible to define specific behaviours and filters. In this sample, filter definitions can be assigned to product categories for the standard category pages and to landing pages. Landing pages are pimcore documents with a special product grid area block within them.

\

column1:
Filter definitions them self are special pimcore objects, where the following aspects can be defined:

\

column2:
• Available order by options (currently not implemented in this demo)
    • \

• Preconditions for visible products in the product grid
    • \

column1:
You also can choose between different filter types, which have influence on the frontend behaviour and on the way the filtering is made in the backend.

\

Available filter types in this demo are:

\

column2:
• Filter Multi Relations: for product index fields technologies and features
    • \

• Filter Multi Select: for product index fields tentTentPegs, name
    • \

• Filter Multi Select from Multi Select: for product index fields color, gender
    • \

• Filter Number Range Selection: for product index fields matsHeight, matsLength, matsWidth, rucksacksLoad, rucksacksVolume, rucksacksWeight
    • \

• Filter Relation: for product index fields technologies and features
    • \

\

column4:
The built-in marketing and pricing rule system provides functions to adapt product and cart pricings based on specific conditions.

\

column2:
• Sold (maximum count of rules applied to current cart)
    • \

• Sales (maximum count of rules applied to orders in total)
    • \

column1:
In the demo, fowling rules are active;

\

column2:
• Order the rucksack Barrow 60 and get a headlamp for free – see Barrow 60
    • \

• If the cart value is above 200 get 10% discount on the cart
    • \

• Free shipping when a handball ball is in the cart
    • \

• Additional gift if the cart value is above 1000
    • \

column4:
pimcore and the E-Commerce-Framework provide several ways to archive Cross Selling functionalities.

\

column1:
Following two ways are implemented in this demo:

\

column2: <li>Manual assignment of related products via object relations:\
<li>Automatic calculation of similar products based on specific categories:\

column3:
• The attributes used for the similarity calculation are defined in the filter definitions. In this demo, category and color are used for the calculations.
    • \

column4:
pimcore provides a very powerful personalization toolkit. For more information have a look at http://www.pimcore.org/en/product/targeting-personalization.

\

column1:
This demo has a very simple use case for personalization integrated. There one persona (outdoor-customer). If an user visits at least 10 outdoor sites, it becomes the corresponding customer. Depending on the most active persona, the portal page is personalized.

\

column4:
For the visualization of the product attributes, this demo uses the output channel toolkit from pimcore. So it is possible to define aspects like appearance, sorting, etc. independent from the product data model. 

\

This demo shows how vouchers can be used within the e-commerce framework. 

\

column1:
One sample voucher code is 'SUMMER' - use it and get free shipping on your cart.

\

column4:
Also have a look at the order backoffice in the pimcore backend. 

\

column1:
There you can search for orders, open detail information of orders and execute actions like cancel or complain items. 

\
